The paper deals with the problem of succinctly representing permutations and functions, which is a fundamental problem in data structures and algorithms. The paper presents solutions that achieve space-time trade-offs and lower bounds, which are typical topics in the sub-category of data structures (cs.DS). The paper also involves combinatorial and information-theoretic arguments, which are relevant to the sub-categories of computational complexity (cs.CC) and information theory (cs.IT). The paper also discusses the redundancy of data structures, which is a topic in the sub-category of discrete mathematics (cs.DM). Finally, the paper mentions the problem of computing powers of permutations and functions, which is related to the sub-category of computational geometry (cs.CG).
